meetup-Bucharest-Data-Science-Meetup-235.description:
This session will be an introductory talk on how to use Neo4J ( https://neo4j.com/ ) in its capacity as a graph analytics engine. The target audience is SQL developers.

We'll start with an overview of Neo4J and its query language Cypher before moving on to a few worked examples where we'll build and query the same data set using first relational databases and then Neo4J.

We'll also cover graph modeling, query optimization and show an example of procedures which were introduced in the 3.0 version of Neo4J.

What is Neo4J?

Here's a good summary by Emil Eifrem, creator of Neo4J:
Most applications today handle data that is deeply associative, i.e. structured as graphs (networks). The most obvious example of this is social networking sites, but even tagging systems, content management systems and wikis deal with inherently hierarchical or graph-shaped data.
This turns out to be a problem because it’s difficult to deal with recursive data structures in traditional relational databases. In essence, each traversal along a link in a graph is a join, and joins are known to be very expensive. Furthermore, with user-driven content, it is difficult to pre-conceive the exact schema of the data that will be handled. Unfortunately, the relational model requires upfront schemas and makes it difficult to fit this more dynamic and ad-hoc data.
A graph database uses nodes, relationships between nodes and key-value properties instead of tables to represent information. This model is typically substantially faster for associative data sets and uses a schema-less, bottoms-up model that is ideal for capturing ad-hoc and rapidly changing data.
meetup-Bucharest-Data-Science-Meetup-235.title: Introduction to Neo4J

meetup-Bucharest-Java-User-Group-2369584.description:
Target audience: Java developers of intermediate level, familiar with the Java language and Java 8 streams.

Speaker: Bogdan Posa
Bogdan is a passionate Java developer working at ING, having a working experience of 5 years. He has previously held another workshop at Bucharest Java User Group on the topic of MVC 1.0, an action-oriented web framework for Java EE (https://bjug.ro/hands-on-lab-mvc-1-0-with-java-ee-8/).

Abstract:
During this 3 hour workshop, we are going to take a look at JSON-P 1.1 (https://json-processing-spec.java.net/) and some of its great new features.

What is JSON-Processing API
JSON-P is an API for parsing and writing JSON objects in Java using Object model API or Stream approach.

What's new in JSON-P 1.1
JSON-P 1.1 introduces a lot of new features like JSON Pointer (RFC6901), JSON Patch (RFC6902) and JSON Merge Patch (RFC7386). The JSON Patch will also have a big impact in developing REST APIs (JAX-RS spec is going to align to JSON-P API).

JSON-P also takes advantages of the Java's stream operations using Lambda expressions, meaning that you can process an JSON object the same way you process a Java stream.

During the hands-on lab sessions we are going to talk about the features introduced in JSON-P 1.1 and we will try use it to solve some real problems.

Duration: 3h

Requirements: 

  - Please bring a laptop with a working Java development environment. Be there at 10:30 (half an hour early) if you need help with setting up your development environment.
  - Java and Java 8 streams knowledge
meetup-Bucharest-Java-User-Group-2369584.title: Workshop - Intermediate - Java API for JSON Processing

meetup-Cluj-Javascripters-236663587.description:
We're super excited to have a special guest invited all the way up from Timisoara for this meetup. It's also one of our first collaborations with sister groups from other cities. So let's all welcome Cassian and hear what he has to say about TypeScript :).


About the presentation:

Supersets of JavaScript have come and gone. Is TypeScript different? This talk will walk you through the ups and downs of adopting TS across 3 different projects, all in 1 intense year. We’ll start with a bit of a context, explaining why it gained momentum, talking about its strong points as well as its pitfalls. We will then look at some examples of using it in real projects. And in the end, we’ll see why TS is a safety-net we should all benefit from… or should we? Come and find out!

About the speaker:

Cassian Lup is a Lead Developer with 3Pillar Global and a co-organizer of TIM.js (http://www.timjs.ro/). He has a passion for the web and tries to look at it with a creative, yet critical eye. He has a passion for all things JS, from trainings and workshops all the way to solving real-life problems with code. When not online, he loves hanging out with his wife and two kids.

Looking forward to seeing you all!

meetup-Cluj-fp-236791113.description:
Programul intalnirii:
6:30 - 7:00 sosirea participantilor + pizza din partea Ullink
7:00 - 8:30 - Denis Rosca - Generic Programming in Scala: Type Class Derivation

Type class derivation is an advanced programming technique that facilitates
safe processing of Scala's case classes and sealed traits in generic
ways while decreasing code duplication and boilerplate.

Traditionally, generic programs tasked with handling of arbitrary ADTs (e.g.
serialization libraries) have made heavy use of runtime reflection APIs while
sacrificing safety. Typically those libraries provide default instances for
"standard" types and various ways of combining them. Library users must write
instances for their own data types in terms of those. This is usually a time
consuming and laborious process, but it is nevertheless completely
mechanical, based entirely on the structure of the types involved. So wouldn't it be nice if we could persuade the Scala compiler to use the
structure of those types and do the work for us? Building on [shapeless's](https://github.com/milessabin/shapeless/)
core generic programming primitives and support for automatic type class
derivation we can! In this talk we'll see how taking advantage of automatic derivation
reduces boilerplate & mechanical code. Along the way we'll discover the
surprisingly simple underlying mechanism that allows us to do that.
meetup-Cluj-fp-236791113.title: Generic Programming in Scala: Type Class Derivation
meetup-Cluj-fp-236791113.venue: Sediul Ullink: Str Victor Deleu nr 1, et 3 (intrarea dinspre Parcul Caragiale), cluj-napoca

meetup-Product-Camp-Bucharest-Meetup-235.description:
Hi Product Campers,

Our next meetup is about “Contractual Risks” by Lawyer Ioana Anda Bălașa

"What are the consequences of not having mentioned the unilateral termination of a service contract?

What options do you have if the client is not paying you?

What are the hidden risks to consider when the lease agreement on your office headquarters is close to expiration?

This workshop, built upon my years of experience in working with both young and experienced entrepreneurs, aims to provide insight into how even the simplest contractual clauses can hide unfortunate consequences that can lead anywhere from loss of profit to loss or reputation or even bankruptcy.

Understanding such issues can help you make an informed decision and mitigate risks or even avoid them altogether."

In the second part we have Open Space and we invite you to come up with your topic or question related to Product Development, Software Product Management, or anything related to our theme.

Agenda:

18:45 - 19:00 Welcome Product Campers

19:00 - 20:00 "Contractual Risks” by Lawyer Ioana Anda Bălașa

20:00 - 20:10 BREAK

20:10 - 21:15 Open Space

See you at Tech Hub Bucharest on Monday, 23rd January 2017!

meetup-Tabara-de-Testare-Cluj-dvppbkywdb.description:
Hello!

This meetup is a do-over session from the testing track at Codecamp Cluj.

The content owner will be Levente Florisca. During this presentation, he aims to cover the following:

What is software testing? It is simply understanding the functionality and architecture of a piece of software and test it until fear of not finding any bugs turns to boredom? But what about coding? Is that required for a tester or it is a knowledge exclusively for developers? Does coding help in the software testing? Is automation a fantasy, in a euphoric world? The difference between software delivering and software developing / testing is a topic which can be discussed until the edge of infinity. The pros and cons of each side will be discussed from a QA point of view.

Levi started to learn, after few years he was asked to tutor, teach and train others in the magical land of automation and testing. He's been holding workshops and training at companies for more than 2 years now, the rest of his info can be tracked on social media.

***About TdT

1. Meetup starts at 18:30.

Please show up at 18:15 to ensure a smooth and proper start of the event.

2. Each meetup has the following workflow:

- by the organizers/facilitators: introduction to Tabara de Testare

- by the speaker: speaker background & then the presentation / workshop itself

- each participant is invited to donate 10 lei to cover the expenses for the location (i.e. Cluj Cowork)

- electronic feedback form - available on the meetup message board after the event

3. TdT online presence:

- Blog: http://tabaradetestare.ro/

- Slideshare: http://www.slideshare.net/tabaradetestare

- Twitter: @tabaradetestare

- Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/Tabara.de.Testare?fref=ts

- Please mention if you do not wish to be photographed or have your picture posted online

Thank you,

TdT Team

meetup-Tabara-de-Testare-Iasi-236665191.description:
Hello everyone,

We're happy to invite you to the first presentation this year about "Testing mobile in the Cloud", to be held by Andrei Diaconu, co-founder Android Iasi.

Find below Andrei's description on the presentation: 

Android has a fragmented ecosystem. There are devices out there with square screens or even no 3G antenna. It’s impossible to test on all of them. But if we write automated tests, then maybe we could run these tests on hundreds of real devices in the cloud. Let’s compare Espresso to Appium and Amazon Device Farm to Firebase Device Lab and see which of these we like more.

Looking forward to see you all!

TdT Team

- implementarea unor design patterns in testarea automata (in afara de Page Objects)

meetup-The-Bucharest-Agile-Software-Meet.description:
What

The code and beer idea is simple enough: we gather in the evening after work, in a pub, have a beer and write some code. It is a social coding event where you can share ideas with other developers. You can come and leave whenever you want.

Why would you come and join us

Meet other programmers
Work on your own project
Help others with their projects
Find someone who might help you with a specific topic
Pair with someone and learn new things
Just hang around and talk to people

How

Bring your laptop and some code that you'll be working on. If you don't have code then think about what you would like to practice during the evening.

There is no predefined agenda. We just meet and work on whatever we feel like.

Important

Please specify what you would like to do during the evening by answering the question "What would you like to practice?" when registering.

Also, as soon as you know you can no longer attend the meeting please change your RSVP to NO immediately. Consider this gesture a sign of respect towards other members of this group who might want to attend in your place.

The number of attendees is limited because of the difficulties of finding a big pub and making reservations for a big group.
meetup-The-Bucharest-Agile-Software-Meet.organizer: The Bucharest Agile Software Meetup Group
meetup-The-Bucharest-Agile-Software-Meet.title: Code and beer

meetup-UX-Casual-Tuesday-236640080.description:
Hi Everyone,

We're getting really excited about this Tuesday FIRST #UXCT where we're going to get to talk about mobile app design, but more importantly about challenges we face while doing so. 

We're really pumped to share our stories with you all and would love to hear yours.


The Venue

For our 1st meetup, we have teamed up with our dear friends from Cluj  Cowork to bring #UXCT right in the heart of Cluj, Emil Isac 23.


Agenda


18:45 - 19:00 — Time to meet up, networking;

19:00 - 19:15 — What is UX Casual Tuesday?

19:15 - 20:15 — Let's talk about mobile apps;

20:15 - 20:30 — Wrap-up and more networking;

Topics

While we'll talk about mobile apps and how we manage to deliver awesome products, we'll cover:

- tips & tricks;

- challenges we face and how to overcome them;

- secret :)

What's your story? :)

Can't wait to meet you all! See you soon!
